First of all, we upload the necessary packages.

library(data.table)   # data table, fread()
library(fastDummies)  # dummy_cols()
library(caret)        # preProcess()
library(neuralnet)    # making neural networks
library(forecast)     # accuracy()
library(dplyr)        # bind_rows()
library(ggplot2)      # plotting

options(scipen = 999) # disable scientific notation

Then, we load our data and keep only the relevant variables for this exercise.

ToyotaCorolla <- fread("ToyotaCorolla.csv") # importing data
# selecting columns cited in exercise
ToyotaCorolla <- ToyotaCorolla[, list(Price, Age_08_04, KM, Fuel_Type, HP, Automatic,
                                      Doors, Quarterly_Tax, Mfr_Guarantee,
                                      Guarantee_Period, Airco, Automatic_airco,
                                      CD_Player, Powered_Windows, Sport_Model, Tow_Bar)]

Please refer to exercise 6.4 for the data exploration phase.

We convert Fuel_Type to dummies using dummy_cols from the fastDummies package and normalize our numerical variables using preProcess from the caret package with the "range" method. This method will scale all our variables to the \([0,1]\) interval.

# creating dummies, remove_first_dummy will only create two dummies for petrol and diesel
ToyotaCorolla <- dummy_cols(ToyotaCorolla, select_columns = "Fuel_Type", remove_first_dummy = TRUE)
# taking out fuel_type from the data now that we have the two dummies
ToyotaCorolla <- ToyotaCorolla[, c(1:3, 5:18)]
# normalizing numerical variables
norm.values <- preProcess(ToyotaCorolla[, c(1:4, 6, 7, 9)], method = "range")
ToyotaCorolla <- predict(norm.values, ToyotaCorolla)

We partition the data into training and validation sets.

set.seed(111)  # set seed for reproducing the partition

# generating training set index
train.index <- sample(c(1:nrow(ToyotaCorolla)), 0.6*nrow(ToyotaCorolla))
# generating validation set index as the complementary of training set
valid.index <- setdiff(c(1:nrow(ToyotaCorolla)), train.index)

# creating data tables Train and Valid using the indexes
Train <- ToyotaCorolla[train.index, ]
Valid <- ToyotaCorolla[valid.index, ]

# removing indexes as they aren't used anymore
rm(train.index, valid.index)

1 Fit neural network models to the data.

We fit three neural networks:

  1. NN2 with one hidden layer of two nodes;
  2. NN5 with one hidden layer of five nodes;
  3. NN55 with two hidden layers of five nodes each.
set.seed(111)

2 Record the RMS error of each neural network for the training data and the validation data.

Now that we have our three neural nets, we will look at the accuracy measures and perform the residual analysis for each of them.

To do so, we must rescale back Price so that the values represent euros.

Recall that to scale the variables, we used the "range" method, which normalizes as follows:

\[X_{norm} = \dfrac{X-a}{b-a}\] with \(a\) and \(b\) the minimal and maximal values taken by the variable. Thus, to scale back, we will compute

\[X = (b-a)X_{norm} + a\]

In our norm.values object, we fetch \(a\) and \(b\) for Price.

norm.values$ranges           # displaying all ranges of scaled variables
##      Price Age_08_04     KM  HP Doors Quarterly_Tax Guarantee_Period
## [1,]  4350         1      1  69     2            19                3
## [2,] 32500        80 243000 192     5           283               36
a = norm.values$ranges[1,1]  # fetching a for Price
b = norm.values$ranges[2,1]  # fetching b for Price

We construct outcome tables for our Train and Valid sets for all three neural networks. These tables contain prices, predicted prices and residuals for both sets.

We start with the tables for NN2.

# creating TrainOutcomes with Values and PredictedValues which are obtained using the predict()
# function on our neuralnetwork and Train set
TrainOutcomes = data.table(Values = Train$Price, PredictedValues = predict(NN2, Train))
# Renaming the column PredictedValues as for some reason I haven't understood, it appears as
# PredictedValues.V1 when created
colnames(TrainOutcomes)[2] = "PredictedValues"

# scaling back the two columns using the formula stated before
TrainOutcomes = (b-a)*TrainOutcomes + a
# defining the Residuals column
TrainOutcomes = TrainOutcomes[, Residuals := Values - PredictedValues]

# same steps for ValidOutcomes
ValidOutcomes = data.table(Values = Valid$Price, PredictedValues = predict(NN2, Valid))
colnames(ValidOutcomes)[2] = "PredictedValues"

ValidOutcomes = (b-a)*ValidOutcomes + a
ValidOutcomes = ValidOutcomes[, Residuals := Values - PredictedValues]

We compute the accuracy measures for both sets and store them.

# we use the accuracy() function from the forecast package
AccNN2Train = accuracy(object = TrainOutcomes$PredictedValues, x = TrainOutcomes$Values)
AccNN2Valid = accuracy(object = ValidOutcomes$PredictedValues, x = ValidOutcomes$Values)
AccNN2Train # displaying accuracy measures for Train
##                 ME     RMSE      MAE      MPE     MAPE
## Test set -1.968602 1091.009 837.9301 -1.29054 8.420052
AccNN2Valid # displaying accuracy measures for Valid
##                 ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE
## Test set -38.50958 1129.469 841.1189 -1.693891 8.488594

We store TrainOutcomes and ValidOutcomes one on top of the other in a table called Outcomes, with a categorical variable that indicates to which set and neural network each row belongs.

The outcomes for the other two neural networks will be added to this Outcomes table later.

# bind_rows from dplyr package allows to stack the two tables together
# we add a new column called Set which takes the value "TrainNN2" or "ValidNN2"
Outcomes = bind_rows(TrainOutcomes[, Set := "TrainNN2"], ValidOutcomes[, Set := "ValidNN2"])

We can now display:

  • Boxplot of Residuals
  • Histogram of Residuals
  • Residuals versus Predicted Values Scatterplot
  • Normal QQ Plot of Residuals

for each of our three neural networks and training/validation sets (six plots in total).

ggplot(data = Outcomes, aes(x = Set, y = Residuals)) +   # plotting residuals
  geom_boxplot() +                                       # making boxplot
  theme_light() +                                        # changing aesthetic theme
  labs(y = "Residuals", title = "Boxplot of Residuals")  # writing labels

# same as previous plot but using geom_histogram to draw the histogram
# facet_wrap in all the following plots allows to draw one plot for Train and one for Valid
ggplot(data = Outcomes, aes(Residuals)) +
  facet_wrap(~Set) +
  geom_histogram(color = "black", fill = "#FA8072", bins = 50) +
  theme_light() +
  labs(title = "Histogram of Residuals")

# same as previous plot but using geom_point to draw points on the plot
ggplot(data = Outcomes, aes(x = PredictedValues, y = Residuals)) +
  facet_wrap(~Set) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_light() +
  labs(x = "Predicted Prices", y = "Residuals", title = "Residuals versus Predicted Values")

# same as previous plot but using geom_qq to draw residuals points on the plot and
# geom_qq_line to draw the straight line
ggplot(data = Outcomes, aes(sample = Residuals)) +
  facet_wrap(~Set) +
  geom_qq() +
  geom_qq_line(color = "#FA8072") +
  theme_light() +
  labs(x = "Standard Normal Quantiles", y = "Empirical Quantiles of Residuals",
       title = "Normal QQ Plot of Residuals")

All four kinds of plots indicate the general tendency of our neural networks to overfit the training data as the complexity of the neural network increases (for Train: the boxplots decrease in height, the residuals’ histograms get higher around zero, outliers become more squished in the scatterplots and the residuals become more normally distributed in the QQ plots).

However, for our validation data, the scenario is very different! NN55 clearly has the worst performances out of the three neural nets, with boxplot and scatterplot showing more spread out or extreme outliers and a stronger departure from normality in the QQ plot. The residuals histogram is similar to the one for NN2, the differences in extreme outliers being too small on the overall count scale to be clearly visible.

For the validation data, NN5 seems to be the better model. Except for the extremely positive residual visible in all Valid boxplots, the rest of residuals are more gathered towards zero than in NN2.This histogram peaks higher at zero as well.

We will now examine the accuracy measures.

2.1 What happens to the RMS error for the training data as the number of layers and nodes increases?

Let us display the accuracy measures for Train. For a recall on the meaning of those measures, please consult exercise 6.4.

AccNN2Train
##                 ME     RMSE      MAE      MPE     MAPE
## Test set -1.968602 1091.009 837.9301 -1.29054 8.420052

##                 ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE
## Test set 0.5428682 1004.488 767.7902 -1.089251 7.738289
AccNN55Train
##                ME     RMSE      MAE       MPE     MAPE
## Test set 1.757064 950.0541 733.9905 -1.005969 7.448774

We can see that the RMSE is decreasing as the neural network becomes more complex, from \(1091€\) to \(950€\). This confirms what we saw in the residual analysis, with the models fitting the training data better as they become more complex. We can note that MAE, MPE and MAPE also decrease. The median error seems to be oscillating but stays close to zero.

Let us display the accuracy measures for Valid.

AccNN2Valid

We can see that NN55 has the highest RMSE. This seems logical, as it had the biggest and most spread out residuals. It also has the biggest ME in absolute value. NN5 looks like the best model here as well, as it has the smallest ME, RMSE, MAE and MPE in absolute value.

2.3 Comment on the appropriate number of layers and nodes for this application.

The evolution of the RMSE for new or unseen data usually follows a positive parabolic shape with respect to the model complexity: It starts out high when the model is very simple, and decreases for a bit, until the model becomes too complex because it starts modeling the noise of the training data (overfitting), at which point the RMSE starts to increase again. To have a low RMSE, we need to find a compromise between the complexity of the model and the danger of overfitting training data.

In other words, what may be happening here is that NN2 is a very simplistic model, NN55 overfits Train and NN5 is a good compromise between the two extremes, resulting as the best version of our three neural networks to predict new data.
